## Step-by-Step Build Procedure (continued)

### Phase 3 — AI Interview Feature (Backend)

#### Step 29: Install new Backend dependencies
```bash
cd Backend
npm install @google/genai zod zod-to-json-schema multer pdf-parse puppeteer
```

| Package | Why |
|---|---|
| `@google/genai` | Official Google Gemini AI SDK for generating structured interview reports |
| `zod` | Schema validation library — defines the expected shape of AI responses |
| `zod-to-json-schema` | (kept for reference, but we use a custom converter for Gemini compatibility) |
| `multer` | Middleware for handling `multipart/form-data` (file uploads) |
| `pdf-parse` | Extracts text content from uploaded PDF resumes |
| `puppeteer` | Headless Chrome for converting AI-generated HTML resumes to PDF |

#### Step 30: Add `GOOGLE_GENAI_API_KEY` to `.env`
```env
MONGO_URI= <your_mongodb_atlas_connection_string>
JWT_SECRET= <your_random_secret_key>
GOOGLE_GENAI_API_KEY= <your_gemini_api_key>
```

> [!TIP]
> Get a free Gemini API key at: https://aistudio.google.com/apikey

#### Step 31: Create `src/middlewares/file.middleware.js` — File upload
```js
const multer = require("multer")

const upload = multer({
    storage: multer.memoryStorage(),
    limits: {
        fileSize: 3 * 1024 * 1024 // 3MB
    }
})

module.exports = upload
```

> [!NOTE]
> `memoryStorage()` stores the uploaded file as a `Buffer` in `req.file.buffer` instead of writing it to disk. This is ideal for passing directly to `pdf-parse`.

#### Step 32: Create `src/models/interviewReport.model.js` — AI report schema

Defines nested sub-schemas for the structured AI output:
- **`technicalQuestionSchema`** — `{ question, intention, answer }` (all required strings)
- **`behavioralQuestionSchema`** — same structure as technical
- **`skillGapSchema`** — `{ skill, severity }` where severity is an enum: `"low" | "medium" | "high"`
- **`preparationPlanSchema`** — `{ day (Number), focus (String), tasks (String[]) }`
- **`interviewReportSchema`** — combines all above + `jobDescription`, `resume`, `selfDescription`, `matchScore` (0-100), `title`, `user` (ObjectId ref), and `timestamps: true`

#### Step 33: Create `src/services/ai.service.js` — Gemini AI integration

This is the core AI layer. Key concepts:

**Why `convertZodToGeminiSchema()` is needed:**
The Gemini API's `responseSchema` expects its own `Type`-based format (`Type.OBJECT`, `Type.STRING`, `Type.ARRAY`, etc.). The popular `zodToJsonSchema()` library produces JSON Schema Draft-07 format (`{ $schema, $ref, definitions }`) which Gemini **completely ignores** — it returns random freeform JSON instead of your defined structure.

The `convertZodToGeminiSchema()` helper recursively walks the Zod schema and converts each type:
| Zod Type | Gemini Type |
|---|---|
| `z.object({...})` | `{ type: Type.OBJECT, properties, required }` |
| `z.array(...)` | `{ type: Type.ARRAY, items }` |
| `z.string()` | `{ type: Type.STRING }` |
| `z.number()` | `{ type: Type.NUMBER }` |
| `z.enum([...])` | `{ type: Type.STRING, enum: [...] }` |
| `z.boolean()` | `{ type: Type.BOOLEAN }` |

**Two exported functions:**
- `generateInterviewReport({ resume, selfDescription, jobDescription })` → calls Gemini with the interview schema → returns parsed JSON
- `generateResumePdf({ resume, selfDescription, jobDescription })` → calls Gemini for HTML resume → converts to PDF with Puppeteer → returns Buffer

#### Step 34: Create `src/controllers/interview.controller.js` — Interview logic

Contains 4 controller functions:
- **`generateInterViewReportController`** — Wrapped in try/catch. Checks if `req.file` exists → parses PDF text with `pdf-parse` → calls `generateInterviewReport()` → saves to MongoDB → returns 201
- **`getInterviewReportByIdController`** — Finds report by `_id` AND `user` (ensures users can only see their own reports) → returns 200 or 404
- **`getAllInterviewReportsController`** — Lists all reports for logged-in user, sorted by newest first. Uses `.select()` to exclude heavy fields (resume, questions, etc.) for performance
- **`generateResumePdfController`** — Fetches report → calls `generateResumePdf()` → sets PDF headers → sends buffer

#### Step 35: Create `src/routes/interview.routes.js` — Interview routes
```js
const express = require("express")
const authMiddleware = require("../middlewares/auth.middleware")
const interviewController = require("../controllers/interview.controller")
const upload = require("../middlewares/file.middleware")

const interviewRouter = express.Router()

interviewRouter.post("/", authMiddleware.authUser, upload.single("resume"),
    interviewController.generateInterViewReportController)

interviewRouter.get("/report/:interviewId", authMiddleware.authUser,
    interviewController.getInterviewReportByIdController)

interviewRouter.get("/", authMiddleware.authUser,
    interviewController.getAllInterviewReportsController)

interviewRouter.post("/resume/pdf/:interviewReportId", authMiddleware.authUser,
    interviewController.generateResumePdfController)

module.exports = interviewRouter
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `upload.single("resume")` middleware **must** come after `authUser` but **before** the controller. The `"resume"` string must match the FormData field name sent by the frontend.

#### Step 36: Update `src/app.js` — Register interview routes
```js
const authRouter = require("./routes/auth.routes")
const interviewRouter = require("./routes/interview.routes")

app.use("/api/auth", authRouter)
app.use("/api/interview", interviewRouter)
```

